One of my coworker's kids had this cube toy that is fun to fidget with. I've tried to recreate it for 3d printing. The current photos are of the toy, not the print, until I can get it printed.

WIP

This model is still a work in progress. I'm still working on the best way to print it. Please let me know if you try to print/assemble this. I'll update once I have it working. If you want to make it, try printing the _test.stl object. That object contains enough pieces to know if your settings will work. For the instructions, 'l' means pin and 'o' means hole, so the _ollo piece has a hole, two pins next two each other, and then another hole.

To assemble the test print, snap the lose hinge to the llll piece. Make sure the hings turns freely. Then put the hinge pins through the holes in the lool piece. Finally snap the first hole of the oooo piece onto one of those two hinge pins. If this piece swivels well, you should be all set!

For each side of the cube (6 total), you'll need either:

  • 4 _oooo, 2 _lll, 2 _ollo and 2 _hinge pieces. (o is hole, l is peg) OR
  • 1 flat_sides & 1 pin_sides (which has all of those pieces grouped together) OR
  • 1 side_set which puts all of the pieces for one side into one stl.

Alternatively color_set has enough pieces to make two sides (if you maintain the original color settings) on a 150mm square bed.

The pieces with pins (llll, ollo, hinge, side_set, color_set, pin_sides) will all need supports touching the buildplate. I found that printing them this way makes the pegs much stronger than if they were vertical.

Because the pins and holes have very small tolerances, the hinges need to be printed at .1mm or finer resolution. The leg pieces can be printed at a coarser resolution, which is why I've separated the two files.

I've found at .08mm resolution, everything prints and works well at 1x scale. If you scale up to 1.5 you can go with a coaser [faster] resolution, but it produces a larger cube.

I've been using grid supports at 20% infill to support the pins works well.

Assemble the sides

Assemble each side, the orientation of the first layer is:
l o o l
l l l l
l l l l
l o o l

where l is a peg, o is a hole.
The top layer uses 4 o o o o pieces in the opposite direction.

Add hinges

The hinges go on the top and bottom sides through the open holes. NOTE the flat sides of the hinges face inside the cube.

Snap all the sides together

Push two hinges together until they snap into place,

Enjoy!

Extruder de type Bowden avec réglage de la pression exercée sur le filament. Ce modèle permet d'extrusion de filament semi-rigide.

Les pièces sont conçues pour être imprimées sans support matériel.
Modélisé avec DesignSpark Mechanical (logiciel gratuit, fichier .rsdoc)

Composants non imprimables :

  • deux vis M3 x 12 pour fixer le sabot (pièce orange sur l'illustration)
  • une vis M3 x 18 faisant office de charnière pour le bras de tension
  • un roulement 684ZZ
  • un ressort : diamètre fil 1.0mm, diamètre intérieur 7mm, diamètre extérieur 9mm, hauteur 22mm
  • une vis tête six pans creux M3 x 16 et son écrou pour régler la tension du ressort
  • un connecteur pneumatique M5
  • un pignon mk8

Assemblage:

Le montage est strictement identique à celui de la première version de l'extruder. Les illustrations ci-dessous sont celles de la v1, mais c'est strictement la même chose pour cette nouvelle version.

  • Montez le roulement sur l'axe du couvercle de bras et assemblez le tout sur le bras

  • Placez l'écrou M3 dans la petite pièce mobile et vissez-y la vis sans tête

  • Sur le sabot, montez le connecteur pneumatique, présentez les deux vis de fixation M3 x 12 et positionnez le tendeur de ressort dans son logement

  • Placez le pignon mk8 sur l'arbre du moteur NEMA17

  • Montez la plaque sur le moteur

  • Vissez le sabot

  • Ajuster le pignon mk8 de sorte que le centre de sa gorge soit parfaitement alignée avec le trou de guidage du filament du sabot.

  • Placez le tendeur dans son logement

  • Placez le ressort au-dessus de son tendeur, mettez le bras en place et vissez sans serrer, le bras doit rester mobile.

  • Réglez la tension à l'aide d'une clé Allen

--- English ---

Bowden extruder with adjustable pressure on the filament.This model allows extrusion of rigid and semi-flexible filaments.

The parts are designed to be printed without material support.
Designed with DesignSpark Mechanical (free software, .rsdoc file)

Nonprintable components are :

  • two screw M3 x 12
  • one screw M3 x 18
  • one 684ZZ ball bearing
  • one spring : Diameter of string: 1 mm, outside diameter: 9 mm, inner diameter: 7 mm, Height: 22 mm
  • one Allen head screw M3 x 16 and his nut
  • one M5 pneumatic connector
  • one MK8 Drive Gear

Assembly:

The assembly is identical to that of the first version of the extrude. The illustrations above are those of the v1, but that's strictly the same for this new version.

title: Boitier ventilé RAMPS Arduino LCD12864 / LCD12864 Arduino RAMPS case with fan

description.text:
--- Videos ---

Impression / Print : https://youtu.be/3JqaZjaI6h4
Assemblage / Assembly : https://youtu.be/cKQOOUaG2FM

--- Français (English below) ---

Voici la version avec ventilateur de mon boitier de commande d'imprimante 3D. A l’intérieur se logent : carte Arduino + RAMPS1.4 + écran LCD 12864 + deux ventilateurs 25x25x10 (max 25x25x15) + un ventilateur 40x40x10.

NB : Les pièces sont conçues pour être imprimées sans support matériel.

L'assemblage compte trois pièces imprimées :

  • le corps principal
  • un panneau latéral
  • un capot pour l'écran LCD

Quincaillerie :

  • 4 vis M3x20
  • 2 vis M3x25 (ou M3x30)
  • 1 connecteur électrique femelle 2,1 x 5,5 mm

Préparation

  1. Imprimez et nettoyez les trois pièces

  2. Supprimez les supports d'impression du panneau latéral :

    • Passage prise USB + passage carte SD
    • Emplacement connecteur électrique

  3. Supprimez les supports du capot écran :

    • Passage bouton
  4. Vérifiez que tout s’emboîte correctement

Assemblage

(Regardez la vidéo d'assemblage : lien en début d'article)

  1. Fixez les ventilateurs 25x25x10 avec des vis M2,5x16. Une vis par ventilateur suffit.

  2. Branchez les deux câbles de l'écran LCD sur la carte RAMPS uniquement.

  3. Glissez les cartes Arduino et RAMPS préalablement câblées dans le boitier.

  4. Attachez les câbles (et la gaine si vous en mettez une) en utilisant un collier plastique.

  5. Glissez le ventilateur 40x40x10 dans son logement.

  6. Montez le connecteur d'alimentation électrique femelle 2.1 x 5.5 sur le capot latéral

  7. Branchez les câbles du ventilateur et de l'alimentation sur le bornier.

  8. Mettez l'écran LCD en place

  9. Placez son capot dessus et fixez-le avec une vis M3x20 en haut et une vis M3x25 en bas

  10. Mettez le capot latéral en place et fixez-le à l'aide des trois vis M3x20 et la vis M3x25 restante qui se place au bas à gauche du capot d'écran.

Et voilà, c'est fini !

Alors, heureux ? ;)

--- English ---

Here is the version of my 3D printer control case with fan. Inside are housed : arduino card + RAMPS1.4 + LCD 12864 + two fans 25x25x10 (max 25x25x15) + one fan 40x40x10.

NB : Parts are designed to be printed without material support.

The assembly consists of three printed parts :

  • the main body
  • a side panel
  • a LCD frame

Hardware:

  • 4 screw M3x20
  • 2 screw M3x25 ou M3x30
  • 1 female electrical connector 2,1 x 5,5 mm

Prep

  1. Print and clean the three parts

  2. Remove the printing supprts from the side panel :

    • USB plug and SD card passages
    • Electrical connector location
  3. Remove the printing support from the LCD frame
    • Button passage

4 - Check that everything fits properly

Assembly

(Watch the assembly video : link at the beginning of the article)

  1. Fix fans 25x25x10 with M2,5x16 screws.One screw by fan is enough.

  2. Connect the two cables of the LCD on the RAMPS board only.

  3. Slide the Arduino and RAMPS cards previously wired into the case

  4. Clamp the cables (and sheath) using a plastic tie

  5. Slide the fan 40x40x10 into place.

  6. Mount the female electrical power connector 2.1 x 5.5 on the side panel

  7. Connect the fan and the power connector on the power terminal block

  8. Put the LCD in place

  9. Place the LCD frame and fix it with one M3x20 screws at the top and one M3x25 screw downstairs

  10. Put the side cover and fasten it with three screws M3x20 and one screw M3x25 which is placed at the bottom left of the LCD frame.

and that's it!

So, happy? ;)

Fibonacci sphere pencil and drillbit holders, can hold bolts, screws, cutlery, 1232 pencils even if you want.

There are 100+ .scad files in a .zip with different numbers of pencils from 8 to 1232 pencils because i had to generate them in a different program.

if you want to use it commercially please tip me, i had to write a SCAD code parser to send matrices from another program. (even just to encourage me to upload more files)

SCAD FILE INSTRUCTIONS:

Notes: RESIZE STL by 380% for drill bit.

The hexagons are 2.0 from corner to corner. a drill bit is 7.333mm largest diameter, so resize to get ~7.6mm it fits for me.....

1 - choose the scad file with the number of pencils/drill bits you want to put away...

2 - resize the spheres to in the SCAD file to suit the number of holes/ holder size.

3 - change the cylinders #fn value from 6 to 20 segments if you want

4 - you can change the sphere number of fragments to make it look nicer, default is 100, it should be more on large spheres. OpenScad buffs can check this code : http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:370871

5 - you can devide it in two halves by copying the scad with a half sphere on top of the array and adjusting the loop number.

that's all ,print the fibonacci spiral/pencil holder

If you want to make fibonacci sphere based anything in scad, this is probably the best place for it. lamps, anything round. Thanks all!

If you have access to a round piece of steel, place a magnet on the steel inside the drill bit holder, then the drill bits will hold in place in a easyfit fasion.

title: Filament mixer / dual extrusion / mixing extruder

description.text:
updated 11/9/2016 - added versions for M5 and BSP1/8 threaded PTFE coupler, and a holder to stop the mixer from tilting.

designed to turn any single bowden hotend setup into a dual extruder setup, just need to add a second extruder. If you use this setup you dont need to calibrate nozzle offsets as its using the one nozzle for both filaments

Need to use some gcode to manage the filament changes otherwise straightforward to assemble, print 2 copies of the body, and assemble using 3x m5 bowden ptfe couplers.

The idea is that when you need to do a filament change, you need to back out the filament into the filament mixer, then push the second filament in, purge, then continue.

Note this is for 1.75mm filament

GCode i used in the tool change script in simplify 3D as follows. No doubt will need to tune for your setup as far as how far to retract etc, just note its always better to retract a bit further than you need, than not enough.

Works fine for PLA and PETG, my stringiest filaments, havent tried TPU yet, suspect i may need to polish the inside of the mixer for it to work properly.

---SNIP---
T[old_tool]
G92 E0
G1 E-30.000 F3600 ;fast initial retract
G1 E-50.000 F300 ; slow down the retract let the filament cool a bit to reduce strings
G1 E-120.000 F3600 ; back out the remaining distance to clear the mixer, youll probably need to tune the length on this for your setup

G1 X150 Y0 F7200 ;go to purge position so you dont squirt filament all over your work

T[new_tool]
;purge new tool
G92 E0
G1 E120.000 F900 ;push the new filament into the hotend
G1 E130.000 F450 ;slow down the push as it enters the heater block
G1 E150.000 F200 ; purge the nozzle, probsbly more than required :)
G1 E148.000 F1800 ; small retract to encourage the purge to snap off
G92 E0

---SNIP---

My setup is a e3d lite using a pair of these extruders http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1708020

This ring / bracelet generator makes finger ring shaped objects that have internal letter-shaped voids that show up as brighter regions of the filament when illuminated with a bright light behind them. On a finger ring they are very difficult to detect, however I expect better results with the scale set larger to make a bracelet. So there is a warning on this one that the design is experiMental, so you might want to borrow the concept only for use in your own designs.

I call it the "hidden void" technique, or maybe you can think up a better name for it. I previously released this concept in my hidden word cross which I can't seem to find in any of my accounts. I just posted the hidden word cross files or at least one version of them, as previously name "digitalbitscross".

Anyway, the concept that i created is very simple, you just design voids of any shape inside your print and they are not viewable under normal circumstances, but when you put a light behind them more light shinges through the void than other places so you see the voids. It's a fun 3D printing concept and I don't know why, but I have checked my accounts on Thingiverse, Pinshape, and YouMagine without finding the cross. Not sure what's up with that. Micro-controlled servo flower WTF?!
A light tracking robot flower! History 2009
Seeing great stuff done with microcontrollers raised the curiosity to create something with an Arduino, too.
After the first HelloWorld, the next step was to connect some sensors to react on input.
Within a short time after more and more parts were assembled playfully, a lovely flower evolved. The first construction resembles a robotic arm. Five individual light sensors mounted on a primitive construction of broken circuit boards, wires and wire-straps create the crucial base for the controller unit. The controller unit evaluates the input signals, makes a decision and sends a reaction in form of calculated signals to the three servos. Currently
Overflo and me are working on an easy-to-build-version of the Flower. And we are about to have a cool version finished ^^ How to use it?
Hm... How to use a flower?
(NOTE: No watering required!!! && Likes Light and 5 Volt)

3x Micro Servos
1x Arduino(or similar)
5x PhotoSensors
Acrylic in 3mm and (probably 1 - 1.5mm depending on the version you want to build)
Some M2 and M3 Screws and Nuts
Some Wire ^^ About the SolarRoboFlowr files :)
The dxf file contains different assembly versions and I hope they will work out for you. You might need to adapt the fittings for the servos and the servo-horns you choose or got. There are different Layers in the File for (I think) two different Servos. Depending on the CAD software you use, you might need to switch some layers off. In this version the fittings for the servos are made of 3 layers (like a sandwich with the servo horn as ham/cheese in the middle), but it turned out the work good when you skip that parts and directly screw the the servo horn onto the arms. I also uploaded 2 Arduino files to operate the microcontroller. (.pde) One with less code - to show how easy it is to build feedback driven robots. And one with more code for calibration, smoothing, gauging and 2 buttons etc... If you are using the less code version you might want to hard-code calibration values for sensors and servos (and pin numbers), otherwise it might move like an insane robot plant. title: MP Select Mini X Gantry Support System

description.text:
UPDATE: For now, I am limiting this to the 6mm version for revision reasons.

This is an X gantry support system for the Monoprice Select Mini (Malyan M200 ) designed to accomplish two things:

1) If your X gantry tends to droop and bed leveling is difficult, this guide rail will immediately correct that and insure the Gantry stays parallel to the bed and perpendicular to the Z axis.

2) It will reduce/eliminate oscillations of the gantry that cause ringing and other visible artifacts on your prints especially at higher print speeds.

INSTRUCTIONS:
This is a 2 variant design which includes a bolt over pylon that will attach over the existing side panel with slightly longer screws or a full replacement panel with a 40mm cooling fan. There is a linear bearing holder that screws on to the end of the X-Gantry with the original screws and than a bearing is zip tied snuggly in place. Finally, a 300mm linear shaft is slid through the linear bearing and clamped into place in the support pylon. The following links will take you to the bearing and linear rail you will need to complete this modification:

Links for 6mm hardware:

Often seen people making online digital oscilloscope, DSO must have digital-analog conversion unit, according to d/a conversion circuit can be divided into two modes: 1. Special ADC chip + single-chip, 2. using single-chip ADC count inside the converter. For the first model I tried two , this circuit is a little more complex, component is more difficult to complete, it is difficult for beginners. The second structure is relatively simple, easyto make, but has a significant drawback, that is, withina narrow bandwidth, one of the more typical works are the overseas friends of http://www.serasidis.gr/circuits/AVR_oscilloscope/avr_oscilloscope.htm, the bandwidth of the oscilloscope only 7.7KHz. code

Produced by experiment, and constantly modify the code, and improved d/a conversion sample rate, very good results have been achieved.

Frequency response: 10Hz-50KHz

description.text:
This is a dock for my nexus 4, specifically based around my phone in my case, so that I don't have to take it out of the case to fit the dock.  
It is a work in progress, the model doesn't include a cut out I needed to make to fit the latch on the side of my case. The pictures are from a slightly earlier version of the model without a front plate which I've decided to add.  
It is parametric-ish in the sense that the material thickness can be adjusted by a variable, as can the size of router bit you're using, but further manual tweaking may be required to make everything still fit if you really change material thickness a lot.  
ultimately I want to actually add a usb plug to make it a proper charing dock, for now there is a small hole (which won't fit a normal cable) in the foot plate piece.

There are three files, one which defines the parts, one which renders them in the final form, and one that renders them into a cut sheet.
Use the cut sheet file to generate gcode for your CNC machine (I guess you could just as easily print the parts as cut them out of something)
Everything should just press-fit together, though you may need to do a little manual sanding of the tabs to make them fit the holes just right. Worth checking the actual thickness of your material and adjusting the material thickness variable in the parts file.

title: Bridge for Lift Style Drawbridge in 1:160 (N) Scale

description.text:
This is the bridge component of an in-progress project to build a lift style drawbridge for N-Scale (1:160). With one substitution this can be printed as a normal bridge. This is a work in progress. The bridge shown is the drawbridge variant. There is also a diagram of the prototype that this model is loosely based upon.

IMPORTANT NOTES

This is modeled (and exported) in full scale so when printing you must use your slicer to reduce it accordingly.
This print requires a smaller than standard nozzle (250 micron ideally). If you are doing work in N-Scale you should have one!

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

125 microns

Notes:

Use a 250 micron nozzle! You might be able to force extrusion width to 300 microns on a larger nozzle but quality will suffer.

Print one base, one top, one roadbed, two end braces, and 16 inner braces. The larger pieces needed to be printed diagonally on my Ultimaker.

Design Tool - Why Full Scale

I use Sketchup Pro and have found that the features for solid modeling do not work well on objects that are modelled at small scale. Hence I model at full scale. I also export at full scale which means that i have to shrink things when I slice them. Just sayin'

comments.text: Check the IMPORTANT NOTE section of my Thing Details!   :-)   I design at full scale and then reduce in my slicer for printing.  N-Scale is .00625 of full scale but it depends on your slicer as to what should be entered.  The other part of that note is also important.  A "standard" 400 micron nozzle will struggle with this bridge.

description.text:
Meet the "ultimaker in a box" or also known as the "noise box", because the box resonates and is a bit loud!

!! PRINTER NOT FULLY TESTED DURING A LONG PERIOD !!
!! It is still work in progress but usable for someone that is crafty.

Do you want a Ultimaker printer in your own size for cheap? This is the answer. Build a box and these printed parts will fit any size (over a certain minimum size of coarse, about 100mm+wanted printsize) Uploaded parts are for ~13mm wood. Adjust wood_thickness in scad to customize for other sizes.

You will have to get the Z axis and printer head from other sources, there are plenty out there to find. I have included my own extruder holder that you can customize, but I have not made any good fan holders for it yet. If you use 6mm rods for the head there are plenty variants for ultimakers to find. I used 8mm because it was what I have so I made a simple holder. .

You need to drill some holes and saw a bit for the rods to connect to motor mounts.

My own experience from this printer is that it works great, And my box was straight so little adjustments was needed to get everything straight. The most important is that the rods get parallel and 90 degrees from each other or it will jam. But I had no problem when building this.

Known issues:

  • The bearings wander out of the mountings, I have used hot glue, but using washers between the bearings and pulleys might be a good idea.
  • The rods can slide inside the bearings, using washers between bearings and pulleys might help. (I have done nothing myself yet)

Notes:

Parts needed

You need:

  • 4pcs 8mm rods for xy
  • 2pc 6mm or 8mm rods for the head.
    GT2 belts, do not need to be closed loop i used 10m bulk and cut to length and put them together in the xy block.
  • 8pcs GT2 pulleys with 8mm bore
  • 4pcs brass bushings 8mm ID 11mm OD (search for ultimaker brass bushing on ebay aliexpress etc..)
  • Bearings F688zz (8x16x5 mm)
  • Long bearings for the head 6 or 8mm
  • screws...
  • and the things I forgot to mention now...
